Description: Read, discuss and write about contemporary and classical works of literature in literary studies. Study classics and new children's authors, especially of interest to primary and secondary education students.

Description: Public relations is about professional and strategic communication. An occupation with global reach and opportunities, our PR graduates enjoy exciting careers here and overseas.

Location: Bldg P, Rooms P3.04 and P3.05, Creative Media Lab

Title: Deakin's Community Garden
Description: Explore our Community Garden and 'collect a free packet of seedlings' while you chat with our health sciences staff and students about health and sustainability careers in food security, community engagement, rehabilitation, mental health, the environment and more.

Title: Challenge yourself on the Deakin Reactor
Description: How do you think your hand-eye coordination compares to elite athletes? Check out our Deakin Reactor and test your skills against professional athletes from the Geelong Cats, the Samsung Australian Diamonds and the Deakin Melbourne Boomers.

Title: Visit the library
Description: Explore our library by taking a look around, or join a casual tour upon request. Discover what makes our students love the library and learn about the spaces, facilities and services available.

Title: Nursing and midwifery clinical simulation centre
Description: Visit our purpose-built learning spaces and simulated clinical spaces, which closely replicate hospital and community environments. Drop in any time to observe our state-of-the-art 3G SimMan patient manikin programmed to simulate a variety of patient scenarios, and chat with academic staff and students to learn more about our courses and equipment.

Title: IT industry panel
Description: Learn about the state of the global IT industry, career opportunities and how studying IT at Deakin will prepare you with the skills in demand from industry professionals and leaders.

Title: Computer science and artificial intelligence
Description: The rise of robotics, artificial intelligence, smart devices and the Internet of Things, along with the widespread use of machine learning over traditional algorithms, has revolutionised computer science. The modern computer scientist needs to understand the devices that generate data, the software and algorithms that consume data, and the application of these techniques to solve challenging problems that face communities, nations and the planet as a whole. In this session, you'll be introduced to some exciting topics covered in our computer science course, taking you on the journey from devices to data and connecting you with an exciting new data-driven world.

Title: Information Technology - cyber security, cloud computing, VR and creative technologies
Description: IT professionals are accelerating digital transformation across industry sectors, driving innovation and enabling economic growth. Our Bachelor of Information Technology provides you with contemporary knowledge, as well as the skills and experience required for a successful career as an IT professional. Explore options available to tailor course outcomes to your career aspirations.

Title: Software engineering
Description: Software engineers are shaping the way we experience life, with innovative solutions for cars, homes, cities, health care and even space. Learn how our innovative software engineering (honours) course prepares you to operate at the intersection of software development and systems engineering, applying specialised robotics and cyber-physical computing skills to drive the design and development of computing solutions that operate within and interact with people, environments and other technologies.

Title: Cyber security
Description: Learn about the exciting field of cyber security, one of the newest and fastest growing areas of information technology. In this talk we'll cover what skills you need to be successful in this field and how Deakin's unique course can prepare you for a fast paced career in cyber security.

Title: Marine biology or marine science? What's the difference?
Description: Find out the difference between our marine biology and marine science degrees, both offering unique diverse marine environments to learn in that will allow you to pursue your passion for marine life and climate preservation. Hear how fieldwork and industry placements will prepare you for a rewarding career.

Title: Zoology and animal science
Description: Study animal diversity, ecology and behaviour, comparative physiology, biochemistry, genetics, evolutionary biology and animal nutrition, with hands-on experience using native Australian fauna and ecosystems. Study zoology and animal science at Deakin and explore animal diversity, ecology and behaviour, comparative physiology, biochemistry, genetics, evolutionary biology and animal nutrition. Immerse yourself in the field with hands-on experience using native Australia fauna and ecosystems.

Title: Wildlife conservation and environmental sustainability
Description: Discover what it�s like to study environmental management and wildlife conservation at Deakin. While environmental management focuses on finding sustainable solutions to the world�s most pressing environmental problems, wildlife and conservation biology offers theoretical and practical experience in areas including wildlife ecology and biodiversity and conservation.

Title: Forensic science
Description: Study our professionally accredited forensic science degree and ensure you�re equipped with the formal training to examine and present scientific evidence. Upon graduation you�ll be ready to work in fields including pharmaceutical and chemical industries, risk analysis, insurance investigation or as a forensic scientist.

Title: Institute for Frontier Materials postgraduate tour
Description: Visit the Institute for Frontier Materials laboratories and see our research into new materials with energy applications. Our masters and PhD students are looking at next generation batteries and thermocells to convert waste low energy heat into power for wearable electronics, such as fitness trackers.
Location: Departing from the Institute for Frontier Materials booth, Career and Course Information Centre
